  &gt;
  &gt; Hi all -
  &gt;
  &gt; Somebody asked me about how &quot;kokuin&quot; were put onto nakago. I&#39;ve always
  refered to these as &quot;hot stamped&quot; but really, I wonder how the smith applied
  these stamps. The nakago being soft (not hardened), were they punched in
  after the sword was finished? It would seem illogical to think the smith
  &quot;heated the nakago&quot; enough to &quot;hot stamp&quot; their seal. Can anyone explain how
  this was done?
  &gt;
  &gt; A related question is about Masahide who did apply a &quot;kokuin&quot; to his
  nakago. Does anyone know if Masahide ever signed his nakago with his
  &quot;kokuin&quot; only? (Not signing his full mei with it.)
  &gt;
